  ],
  "rationale": "<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The correct answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"63\"><mn>63</mn></math>. It's given that triangles <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper A upper B upper C\"><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>C</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper D upper E upper F\"><mi>D</mi><mi>E</mi><mi>F</mi></math> are congruent with angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper A\"><mi>A</mi></math> corresponding to angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper D\"><mi>D</mi></math>. Corresponding angles of congruent triangles are congruent and, therefore, have equal measure. It's given that the measure of&nbsp;angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper A\"><mi>A</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"27 degree\"><mn>27</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. It follows that the measure of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper D\"><mi>D</mi></math> is also <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"27 degree\"><mn>27</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. It's given that angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper E\"><mi>E</mi></math> is a right angle. Therefore, the measure of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper E\"><mi>E</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"90 degree\"><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\"><mi>x</mi></math> represent the measure, in degrees, of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper F\"><mi>F</mi></math>. Since the measures of the angles in a triangle sum to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"180 degree\"><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>, it follows that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"27 plus 90 plus x equals 180\"><mn>27</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn></math>, or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"117 plus x equals 180\"><mn>117</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn></math>. Subtracting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"117\"><mn>117</mn></math> from both sides of this equation yields <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x equals 63\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>63</mn></math>. Therefore, the measure, in degrees, of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"upper F\"><mi>F</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"63\"><mn>63</mn></math>.</p>",
